WEBVTT

00:05.964 --> 00:09.426
[siren wailing]

00:09.509 --> 00:13.388
[tense music]

00:13.471 --> 00:16.558
- So this is
the Battle of London...

00:18.643 --> 00:21.479
The day we as good as won
the English Civil War.

00:22.981 --> 00:27.110
To be fair, it was mostly
because of him...

00:27.193 --> 00:28.862
Gully Troy,

00:28.945 --> 00:31.448
or Captain Blighty,
as he came to be known.

00:31.531 --> 00:34.659
Now, you could say he was a
science experiment gone wrong.

00:34.743 --> 00:36.536
Forward!

00:36.619 --> 00:38.955
But there was nobody else
like him.

00:40.206 --> 00:42.083
At least
that's what we thought.

00:42.167 --> 00:45.253
[The Clash's "Should I Stay
or Should I Go"]

00:45.336 --> 00:46.671
Five years on,

00:46.755 --> 00:50.049
turns out
he was just the first one.

00:50.133 --> 00:54.053
Some blame nuclear clouds,
drugs, mad scientists.

00:54.137 --> 00:58.141
No one knew the reasons,
but they made people nervous.

00:58.224 --> 01:01.603
Me?
I saw a business opportunity.

01:01.686 --> 01:07.358
♪ ♪

01:08.735 --> 01:09.736
Excuse me, mate.

01:09.819 --> 01:12.280
- [groaning softly]

01:12.363 --> 01:15.325
- Do you know you're
frightening that young lady?

01:15.408 --> 01:17.160
- No, I'm not.

01:17.243 --> 01:18.995
- You've got your hand
round her neck.

01:19.078 --> 01:21.164
Of course she's frightened.
- That's not my hand.

01:21.247 --> 01:22.999
It does what it wants,
this arm.

01:23.082 --> 01:24.501
- Whose arm is it?

01:24.584 --> 01:26.669
- Woke up in a hospital,
and the bastard were there.

01:26.753 --> 01:29.172
- Fucking scientists.

01:29.255 --> 01:32.217
They take some diabolical
liberties, don't they?

01:32.300 --> 01:34.844
- You learn to live with it.

01:34.928 --> 01:37.597
Who are you?
- Name's Alfie Pennyworth.

01:37.680 --> 01:38.973
You?

01:39.057 --> 01:42.519
- Doesn't matter who I am.
Nobody cares.

01:42.602 --> 01:44.729
- Not true, son.
I care.

01:44.813 --> 01:46.105
- [scoffs]
Fuck off.

01:46.189 --> 01:48.191
Government, are you?
- Nah.

01:48.274 --> 01:51.236
Government pays me 500 quid
for every one of your sort

01:51.319 --> 01:53.363
I bring in for 'em.

01:53.446 --> 01:54.739
- 500 quid?

01:54.823 --> 01:57.534
That's good money, that.
- That's why I'm here.

01:57.617 --> 02:00.703
- But suppose this arm
don't want to be brought in.

02:00.787 --> 02:02.831
You gonna shoot me?

02:02.914 --> 02:04.332
- I don't want to.

02:04.415 --> 02:06.668
Dead, you're only worth a pony,
if that.

02:06.751 --> 02:08.670
- [scoffs]

02:08.753 --> 02:11.047
- Now you got any ideas?
That girl needs our help.

02:11.131 --> 02:13.424
- Well,
if you have a go at him,

02:13.508 --> 02:16.886
I dare say he'll drop her
and have a go at you.

02:16.970 --> 02:18.096
- Don't worry, love.

02:18.179 --> 02:20.181
We'll soon have you
out of here.

02:20.265 --> 02:22.809
All right, then.
[clears throat]

02:22.892 --> 02:25.603
[crowd gasps]

02:25.687 --> 02:27.772
Come and have a go if you
think you're hard enough.

02:27.856 --> 02:29.607
[metal clangs]

02:30.984 --> 02:33.736
[dramatic music]

02:33.820 --> 02:34.737
Whoa!

02:34.821 --> 02:36.906
- [grunts]

02:38.867 --> 02:39.784
- Sorry, mate.

02:39.868 --> 02:41.744
[low beeping]

02:41.828 --> 02:43.788
- We secured the enhancement.

02:43.872 --> 02:45.248
He's safe to transport.

02:45.331 --> 02:46.583
Don't worry, son.

02:46.666 --> 02:49.168
We're gonna treat you right.
I promise.

02:53.339 --> 02:54.716
- Excuse me, ma'am.

02:54.799 --> 02:57.510
- MI5 science department.

02:57.594 --> 03:00.054
Hi, Lucius.
What do we got?

03:00.138 --> 03:01.347
- Martha, nice to see you.

03:01.431 --> 03:03.349
We've got
an unregistered cyber-limb.

03:03.433 --> 03:04.851
Probably Russian, I'd say.

03:04.934 --> 03:07.270
Some sort of plasma drive,
I suspect,

03:07.353 --> 03:08.563
coupled to a gyro-transistor--

03:08.646 --> 03:10.148
- I'm kind of in a hurry,
Lucius.

03:10.231 --> 03:11.774
So do you want him,
or does he go to the police?

03:11.858 --> 03:13.651
- Unknown technology
and a violent presentation,

03:13.735 --> 03:14.777
definitely a keeper.

03:14.861 --> 03:16.821
- Okay.
All yours.

03:19.157 --> 03:20.825
There you go.
- Mrs. Wayne.

03:20.909 --> 03:22.535
- Oh, Mr. Pennyworth.

03:22.619 --> 03:24.871
This is your third catch
this month, I believe.

03:24.954 --> 03:26.623
Business is good.
- Don't go thinking

03:26.706 --> 03:29.459
you can drop the price just
'cause we're doing all right.

03:29.542 --> 03:31.544
- Well, when the price was set,
nobody imagined

03:31.628 --> 03:33.755
so many of these Pdubs
would emerge.

03:33.838 --> 03:35.131
- P-what?

03:35.214 --> 03:37.717
- PWEs--
people with enhancements.

03:37.800 --> 03:39.135
That's the official usage now.

03:39.218 --> 03:42.138
- NGs, more like--
nutters with gizmos.

03:42.221 --> 03:43.389
- [laughs]

03:43.473 --> 03:45.141
- You can always ask
someone else.

03:45.224 --> 03:47.518
Plenty of cowboys around
who will do the job cheaper.

03:47.602 --> 03:50.688
- Relax.
You're gonna get your money.

03:50.772 --> 03:52.106
- How's baby Sam?

03:52.190 --> 03:53.858
- She's not a baby anymore.

03:53.942 --> 03:55.985
She's turning five next week.

03:56.069 --> 03:57.445
Oh, fuck.

03:57.528 --> 04:00.782
I'm late. I've got to run.
Have a nice day, people.

04:01.824 --> 04:04.410
- Hoity little madame,
that one.

04:04.494 --> 04:06.871
I don't know
what you see in her.

04:06.955 --> 04:08.539
- Money.

04:08.623 --> 04:10.249
- Give over.

04:10.333 --> 04:12.085
You two have got form.

04:12.168 --> 04:14.671
- Bollocks, we have.

04:14.754 --> 04:17.257
- Tell us
you never snogged her.

04:17.340 --> 04:19.425
Tell us.

04:19.509 --> 04:21.010
- I never.

04:21.094 --> 04:22.845
- Bloody hell.

04:22.929 --> 04:24.097
- I said I never.

04:24.180 --> 04:26.265
- Un-fucking-believable.

04:26.349 --> 04:29.686
- Fuck the pair of you.
- [laughs]

04:29.769 --> 04:32.730
[adventurous music]

04:32.814 --> 04:39.904
♪ ♪

05:22.572 --> 05:25.658
[thunder rumbling]

05:41.758 --> 05:44.385
- We're here, Doc.
It's just down the street.

05:44.469 --> 05:47.388
[dramatic music]

05:47.472 --> 05:52.435
♪ ♪

05:52.518 --> 05:53.895
All clear.

05:55.646 --> 05:58.066
You okay, Doc?

05:58.149 --> 05:59.817
You look scared.
- No.

05:59.901 --> 06:01.152
Yeah, I'm fine.

06:01.235 --> 06:03.821
- Well, don't worry.
You're safe with me.

06:03.905 --> 06:06.449
- [laughs]
Well, that's ironic.

06:06.532 --> 06:08.451
- How so?

06:08.534 --> 06:11.496
[sinister music]

06:11.579 --> 06:13.122
♪ ♪

06:13.206 --> 06:16.709
- [whimpers]
I'm terribly sorry.

06:21.923 --> 06:26.511
[birds chirping, dogs barking]

06:26.594 --> 06:29.263
- [hums]
- It's National Science Day.

06:29.347 --> 06:32.683
And a ceremony was held
at Uxted Air Force Base

06:32.767 --> 06:34.769
to honor heroes and heroines

06:34.852 --> 06:37.438
of the recent global struggle
for freedom.

06:37.522 --> 06:39.023
- "Kind and mature female."

06:39.107 --> 06:41.901
"Go ahead"...
[sighs]

06:41.984 --> 06:44.654
- ...Captain Gulliver Troy,
better known, of course,

06:44.737 --> 06:47.406
as good old Captain Blighty.
- Mm.

06:47.490 --> 06:50.827
- Today we celebrate
the wonders of modern science,

06:50.910 --> 06:54.330
new frontiers,
astonishing possibilities.

06:54.413 --> 06:55.998
Human potential
has never been greater.

06:56.082 --> 06:57.500
[door closes]

06:57.583 --> 07:01.671
Godlike powers
are within our grasp, but...

07:01.754 --> 07:04.048
- Or not.

07:04.132 --> 07:06.843
- Take care, love.
- See you later, Alfie.

07:06.926 --> 07:10.638
- The recent nuclear conflict
between the USA and Russia,

07:10.721 --> 07:13.182
the tragic fates
of Kyiv and Miami

07:13.266 --> 07:15.852
have proven that hard truth.

07:15.935 --> 07:18.354
We must, all of us,

07:18.437 --> 07:21.190
be ever vigilant
that nuclear war...

07:21.274 --> 07:24.861
- [clicks tongue, scoffs]
- Never happens again.

07:24.944 --> 07:26.863
- He does go on, doesn't he?
- [chuckles]

07:26.946 --> 07:28.114
- Any toast going?

07:28.197 --> 07:30.533
- Plenty of toast,
no marmalade.

07:30.616 --> 07:32.201
- No marmalade?

07:32.285 --> 07:35.413
- Oh, I've got a job as well,
you know?

07:35.496 --> 07:37.540
I can't be down in the shops
all day.

07:37.623 --> 07:38.749
- Yeah.

07:42.211 --> 07:44.046
- I wish
you'd find a nice girl.

07:44.130 --> 07:46.215
- You just saw one.

07:46.299 --> 07:48.759
- What's her name?

07:48.843 --> 07:50.011
- Bridget.

07:50.094 --> 07:52.054
- [exhales sharply]
You had to think.

07:52.138 --> 07:54.557
- [chuckles]
Well, I'll get some marmalade

07:54.640 --> 07:58.227
on the way home, then, shall I?
- You do that.

07:58.311 --> 08:00.354
- [sighs]

08:01.981 --> 08:03.357
- [giggles]
- No! Please!

08:03.441 --> 08:05.193
No, don't hurt me! No! No!
[door opens]

08:05.276 --> 08:07.528
- Tell me the truth!
- No, I'm not scared of you.

08:07.612 --> 08:08.613
I'll never tell!
[door closes]

08:08.696 --> 08:09.655
- You will tell,

08:09.739 --> 08:11.240
or I will cast a spell on you!

08:11.324 --> 08:12.617
- No! Please don't!

08:12.700 --> 08:14.368
Daddy, help.
An evil witch has caught me.

08:14.452 --> 08:17.205
- Oh, my gosh.
Well, never fear.

08:17.288 --> 08:19.165
I am here to save the day.
[door opens]

08:19.248 --> 08:20.875
Listen here, you wicked witch.
[door closes]

08:20.958 --> 08:22.460
You leave
that poor clown alone.

08:22.543 --> 08:24.086
- No! No!
- [screams]

08:24.170 --> 08:26.172
Oh, my gosh.
She's such a powerful witch.

08:26.255 --> 08:28.633
She's not just casting a spell.
She's bashing into me.

08:28.716 --> 08:30.009
And there's Mrs. P.

08:30.092 --> 08:31.427
Good morning, Mrs. P.
- Good morning.

08:31.510 --> 08:32.762
- Mrs. P!
- Hi, Mrs. P.

08:32.845 --> 08:34.096
I've got to run.

08:34.180 --> 08:35.932
- Uh, oh, my gosh,
So have I.

08:36.015 --> 08:37.391
- Aw.

08:39.852 --> 08:41.187
- Hey.

08:41.270 --> 08:43.105
Have a great day at the office.
- I will.

08:43.189 --> 08:44.398
You too.

08:48.194 --> 08:50.279
[sighs]

09:05.253 --> 09:08.047
[engine turning over]

09:08.130 --> 09:10.925
- Rave on, popsters--
here's the latest smasheroo

09:11.008 --> 09:14.804
from that supermod songbird
with the groovy beat, Sandra!

09:14.887 --> 09:20.601
- ♪ I hear you whispering ♪

09:20.685 --> 09:26.524
♪ But nobody's there ♪

09:26.607 --> 09:32.530
♪ My eyes
are still lingering ♪

09:32.613 --> 09:38.327
♪ On your empty chair ♪

09:38.411 --> 09:44.500
♪ My darling,
don't tell me it's true ♪

09:44.583 --> 09:48.045
♪ I'll wait here forever ♪

09:48.129 --> 09:53.843
♪ For you ♪

09:53.926 --> 09:59.515
♪ 'Cause
I gave you everything ♪

09:59.598 --> 10:05.855
♪ My heart in your hands ♪

10:05.938 --> 10:10.151
♪ And what did you
give to me? ♪

10:10.234 --> 10:16.157
♪ I'm left with candlesticks
and caravans ♪

10:16.240 --> 10:22.955
♪ Just left with candlesticks
and caravans ♪

10:23.039 --> 10:24.123
♪ ♪

10:24.206 --> 10:25.875
♪ I cling to your memory ♪

10:25.958 --> 10:28.711
- How's business? Good?
Excellent.

10:28.794 --> 10:30.713
Yeah, it looks nice.
Thanks.

10:30.796 --> 10:33.549
[indistinct chatter]

10:33.632 --> 10:36.510
["Candlesticks and Caravans"
continues on radio]

10:36.594 --> 10:41.974
- ♪ I'm lost in revelry ♪

10:42.058 --> 10:43.809
♪ I yearn just for more ♪

10:43.893 --> 10:45.978
- [whistles]

10:51.359 --> 10:53.569
- Yes, but wait--

10:53.652 --> 10:55.071
But--

10:55.154 --> 10:56.405
- Morning, Chadley.

10:56.489 --> 10:58.449
- I'm not saying
I don't believe you.

10:58.532 --> 11:02.703
I'm saying you're letting us
down most grievously.

11:03.913 --> 11:06.082
- But it's Miss Dixon
from Raven HQ.

11:06.165 --> 11:07.625
It's definitely her.

11:07.708 --> 11:10.252
- Frankly,
Bet, I really don't care.

11:10.336 --> 11:12.755
Listen--
- Okay, I'll sort it meself.

11:12.838 --> 11:14.256
- But--

11:14.340 --> 11:15.883
Hello?

11:21.222 --> 11:22.473
No problems.

11:22.556 --> 11:25.267
There's a client in distress,
waiting.

11:30.523 --> 11:32.942
- She's been gone
two weeks now,

11:33.025 --> 11:35.236
which is completely unlike her.

11:35.319 --> 11:37.780
She's never been gone so long
without calling me.

11:37.863 --> 11:42.701
- Hmm, Miss Hamperton,
Jessica's 18, you say?

11:42.785 --> 11:44.412
She's an adult.

11:44.495 --> 11:46.956
She can come and go
as she likes.

11:47.039 --> 11:50.418
- I went to the nightclub
where she was last seen.

11:50.501 --> 11:52.378
Oh, my Lord.

11:52.461 --> 11:55.464
You can't imagine
a more vile and sordid place.

11:55.548 --> 11:59.301
She's in some kind of trouble.
I'm sure of it.

11:59.385 --> 12:01.512
- Have her parents
tried to find her?

12:03.139 --> 12:05.891
- The Thistles are
an eminent couple.

12:05.975 --> 12:08.686
Sir Arnulf is head
of the Thistle Corporation.

12:08.769 --> 12:11.647
They lead very busy
public lives.

12:11.730 --> 12:15.651
They have entrusted me
with making enquiries.

12:15.734 --> 12:19.572
I've been her nanny
since she was two years old.

12:19.655 --> 12:21.615
- Her parents are the ones
to get an invoice, though,

12:21.699 --> 12:22.908
are they?
- Oh, yes.

12:22.992 --> 12:25.286
They'll pay
any reasonable costs.

12:25.369 --> 12:27.329
- We'll have a look
for Jessica, then.

12:27.413 --> 12:28.831
I expect
she's perfectly all right.

12:28.914 --> 12:31.834
- Thank you.
Thank you so much.

12:31.917 --> 12:34.503
Everyone says you're the best,
Mr. Pennyworth.

12:34.587 --> 12:37.631
- Oh.
- You'll find her for me.

12:37.715 --> 12:38.841
- We will, Miss.

12:38.924 --> 12:41.385
Myself or one of my associates.

12:47.933 --> 12:50.311
When she ever comes in,
get Bet on this one.

12:50.394 --> 12:51.937
She's the best
with missing girls.

12:52.021 --> 12:55.191
- In, she will not be.
Busy with her own affairs.

12:55.274 --> 12:56.817
- She's supposed to be here.

12:56.901 --> 12:59.737
- I told her this precisely.

12:59.820 --> 13:01.697
- It's down to me again, then.

13:01.780 --> 13:04.074
I'm supposed to be taking
a managerial role.

13:04.158 --> 13:05.367
Where is she?

13:05.451 --> 13:08.078
- I regret to say
she is seeking revenge.

13:08.162 --> 13:09.747
- Revenge?
From who?

13:09.830 --> 13:11.207
- She's looking for John Salt

13:11.290 --> 13:13.709
so she can kill him
in some painful fashion.

13:13.792 --> 13:15.085
- Fuck's sake.

13:15.169 --> 13:17.046
And get someone in
to sort out this place.

13:17.129 --> 13:18.422
It looks like shit.

13:29.350 --> 13:31.435
- Hello, Miss Dixon.

13:31.519 --> 13:33.229
Remember me?

13:34.563 --> 13:36.482
Get in there now!

13:38.025 --> 13:39.777
- What on Earth?
- Shut up.

13:41.403 --> 13:42.279
Sit down.

13:42.363 --> 13:43.989
Sit down.
You too.

13:44.073 --> 13:46.033
- Who are you?
Who is she?

13:46.116 --> 13:47.952
- Never you mind who I am.

13:48.035 --> 13:50.204
She knows, don't you?

13:50.287 --> 13:51.413
Hmm.

13:51.497 --> 13:53.916
How have you
been keeping, then?

13:53.999 --> 13:55.501
- Well, thank you.

13:55.584 --> 13:58.295
- Good, good.
No trauma, then?

13:58.379 --> 14:01.423
No regrets for your days
as a Nazi thug?

14:01.507 --> 14:02.758
Not got sleepless nights

14:02.841 --> 14:04.802
fretting about
all those ruined lives?

14:04.885 --> 14:07.346
- Now, look here--
- Shut it, you.

14:07.429 --> 14:11.392
It's taken us nigh on
five years to find this bitch,

14:11.475 --> 14:13.811
and I'll have my say.

14:14.979 --> 14:17.898
You look like
a geography teacher.

14:17.982 --> 14:19.984
Is that what you are,
a geography teacher?

14:20.067 --> 14:21.151
- No.

14:21.235 --> 14:24.446
- I fucking hate
geography teachers.

14:24.530 --> 14:26.282
What's the capital
of Portugal, eh?

14:26.365 --> 14:27.783
Eh?

14:27.866 --> 14:30.911
- Lisbon?
- Exactly! Who gives a fuck?

14:30.995 --> 14:32.746
[baby crying]

14:34.373 --> 14:38.210
- Oh, wow.
Your heart sounds much better.

14:38.294 --> 14:39.670
That's great.

14:39.753 --> 14:43.299
You want to listen?
Yeah? Okay.

14:43.382 --> 14:46.010
Hold these there.
That's it.

14:46.093 --> 14:48.095
And we're gonna listen here.

14:51.015 --> 14:52.808
It's cool, huh?

14:52.891 --> 14:54.685
It sounds like the ocean.

14:54.768 --> 14:57.396
[chuckles]
She's gonna be fine.

14:57.479 --> 14:59.982
- Oh, thank you, Doctor.
- She's a little fighter.

15:01.984 --> 15:05.112
[indistinct chatter]

15:08.490 --> 15:10.659
- He's been dead a week or so.

15:10.743 --> 15:14.246
The murder weapon was
a doctor's surgical scalpel.

15:14.330 --> 15:15.664
Took a while to ID him,

15:15.748 --> 15:17.750
but we now know him
to be an American--

15:17.833 --> 15:20.544
a CIA agent in
the tactical security section.

15:20.628 --> 15:22.921
- A gunman?
- Precisely.

15:23.005 --> 15:25.549
But the Americans
haven't enquired about him,

15:25.633 --> 15:26.884
which tells us what?

15:26.967 --> 15:29.053
- They don't us to know
he was here,

15:29.136 --> 15:30.888
which means
he was doing something

15:30.971 --> 15:32.681
he shouldn't have been doing...

15:32.765 --> 15:34.642
something big.
- Yes.

15:34.725 --> 15:37.561
I want you to find out
exactly what that was.

15:37.645 --> 15:39.563
The Commonwealth summit's
coming up.

15:39.647 --> 15:42.024
We can't afford any scandals.

15:42.107 --> 15:43.567
- Understood.

15:45.194 --> 15:46.737
Oh, fuck.
- What?

15:46.820 --> 15:49.365
- The time.
Will that be all, sir?

15:49.448 --> 15:52.576
- The time seems to be
a common theme recently.

15:52.660 --> 15:55.454
Forgive me, Martha,
if I ask again...

15:55.537 --> 15:58.624
are you--
can you handle it?

15:58.707 --> 16:00.584
- Yes, sir.
Yes, I can.

16:00.668 --> 16:03.462
And I am handling
both sides of my life.

16:03.545 --> 16:05.547
- Are you all finished,
sweetheart?

16:05.631 --> 16:07.424
[door opens, closes]
- Hi!

16:07.508 --> 16:09.009
- Hi, Mommy.

16:09.093 --> 16:10.928
- Hi, baby.
Hi, Mrs. P.

16:11.011 --> 16:12.262
I'm so sorry I'm late.

16:12.346 --> 16:15.808
There was another crisis
at the office.

16:15.891 --> 16:18.227
- Martha, where have you been?
You're late.

16:18.310 --> 16:20.562
- I know.
It was paperwork.

16:20.646 --> 16:23.232
- Well, I wish you'd let me
know when you're gonna be late.

16:23.315 --> 16:26.610
- Did I miss anything?
- Uh, yes, actually.

16:26.694 --> 16:28.821
My father's here.
- What?

16:28.904 --> 16:30.698
- He's come to stay with us
for a few days,

16:30.781 --> 16:32.491
with a lady friend,
a surprise visit.

16:32.574 --> 16:34.868
- No, but--but you hate
your father.

16:34.952 --> 16:38.205
You haven't spoken in years.
- Well, that's--

16:38.288 --> 16:40.165
That may be, but, um...

16:41.667 --> 16:44.753
- Well, well, well,
this must be the little lady

16:44.837 --> 16:46.839
that stole my son's heart away.

16:46.922 --> 16:48.382
- Uh--
- Patrick Wayne.

16:48.465 --> 16:50.592
- Wow.
What a lovely surprise.

16:50.676 --> 16:53.220
- And this is my very good
friend Virginia Devereaux.

16:53.303 --> 16:57.933
- Oh, so, so happy
to meet you, Martha.

16:58.016 --> 17:00.018
[light laughter]

17:01.186 --> 17:04.189
- Uh, well... [clears throat]
well, this is nice.

17:04.273 --> 17:06.692
[dramatic music]

17:06.775 --> 17:10.070
[distant dog barking]

17:16.201 --> 17:19.329
- What's the baby's name?
- Julie.

17:21.915 --> 17:23.959
- Hello, Julie.

17:24.042 --> 17:26.837
You know what I want,
don't you?

17:26.920 --> 17:28.922
Where's John Salt?

17:29.006 --> 17:31.091
That's what I want to know.

17:31.175 --> 17:33.969
Where's John Salt?

17:34.052 --> 17:35.387
- We don't know.

17:35.471 --> 17:36.930
- Oh, like fuck you don't!

17:37.014 --> 17:39.475
He didn't escape from prison
on his tod, did he?

17:39.558 --> 17:41.059
There were a whole network
of old Ravens

17:41.143 --> 17:42.311
helping him, obviously.

17:42.394 --> 17:44.605
- We don't know where he is.
I swear.

17:44.688 --> 17:47.816
If we knew where he was,
I'd tell you.

17:47.900 --> 17:49.568
I'm not a Raven,
not anymore.

17:49.651 --> 17:51.445
- [scoffs]
- Neither of us.

17:51.528 --> 17:53.864
- We have nothing to do
with politics.

17:53.947 --> 17:57.117
- You'll tell us where he is,
or mark my words,

17:57.201 --> 18:00.496
there'll be guts
on this rug.

18:00.579 --> 18:02.664
[Robin Tower's "I Can't Wait
Much Longer" playing]

18:02.748 --> 18:07.086
- ♪ There beneath
the diamond sky ♪

18:07.169 --> 18:09.505
♪ ♪

18:09.588 --> 18:14.176
♪ Caviar
and the moonlight wine ♪

18:14.259 --> 18:16.804
♪ ♪

18:16.887 --> 18:21.683
♪ She hasn't yet
made up her mind ♪

18:21.767 --> 18:24.561
♪ If she'll take me ♪

18:24.645 --> 18:27.689
♪ ♪

18:27.773 --> 18:32.277
♪ See, my love,
it's stoned indeed ♪

18:32.361 --> 18:33.695
- Wow.

18:33.779 --> 18:36.824
I haven't seen you cats around
in a while.

18:36.907 --> 18:39.117
How's the strong-arm game?

18:39.201 --> 18:42.496
- The security business
is good.

18:42.579 --> 18:44.122
How's the pimp trade?

18:44.206 --> 18:48.585
- The hospitality business is,
you know, ticking along.

18:48.669 --> 18:51.421
- Have you seen her?

18:51.505 --> 18:54.216
- I've seen
this photo before, yeah.

18:54.299 --> 18:55.551
- When was that?

18:55.634 --> 18:57.094
- A couple of days ago.

18:57.177 --> 18:58.428
- This old bird comes in

18:58.512 --> 19:00.597
and shows me
this very same picture.

19:00.681 --> 19:03.225
Asks me have I seen her.

19:03.308 --> 19:04.309
- And what did you say?

19:04.393 --> 19:07.896
- I said I've never seen her.

19:09.523 --> 19:11.066
- But you were lying.

19:12.901 --> 19:14.903
- And what makes you say that?

19:14.987 --> 19:17.573
- I know your style,
Mr. Renley.

19:17.656 --> 19:18.824
If you had never seen the girl,

19:18.907 --> 19:20.325
you'd have said
you had seen her

19:20.409 --> 19:22.202
and squeezed some dosh
out of the poor old bird,

19:22.286 --> 19:24.538
but because you have seen her
and you know she's in trouble,

19:24.621 --> 19:27.249
you thought it best
to keep mum.

19:27.332 --> 19:29.418
- You see,
that is nonsense.

19:29.501 --> 19:33.881
- Mr. Renley, do you really
want it to go that way?

19:33.964 --> 19:35.674
All due respect
to your man there,

19:35.757 --> 19:38.927
an altercation won't end well
for you.

19:39.011 --> 19:42.389
- You think you're really hard,
don't you?

19:43.599 --> 19:46.768
- Yeah, I suppose we do.

19:46.852 --> 19:48.228
Why'd you ask?
[bangs on desk]

19:48.312 --> 19:50.606
Hmm?
Do you think we're wrong?

19:50.689 --> 19:53.442
Are we not hard? No?

19:53.525 --> 19:58.655
♪ ♪

19:58.739 --> 20:03.118
- All right, I-I saw her
around a couple of times.

20:03.201 --> 20:05.746
And last time, she was hanging
out with that Sister Susie,

20:05.829 --> 20:10.500
and she left with her,
so, you know...

20:10.584 --> 20:15.631
[laughing]
You boys are so square.

20:17.591 --> 20:19.301
Sister Susie.

20:19.384 --> 20:21.637
She runs
the Inner Peace Ashram.

20:21.720 --> 20:24.848
It's the hippest cult in town.
- Yeah, I've heard the name.

20:24.932 --> 20:26.475
But why is she trouble?

20:26.558 --> 20:28.352
- She feeds these kids
psychedelic drugs

20:28.435 --> 20:30.020
so they don't know
their own name.

20:30.103 --> 20:33.065
Sometimes they wake up
happy and enlightened,

20:33.148 --> 20:36.276
but sometimes they wake up sad

20:36.360 --> 20:38.320
and in a brothel.

20:38.403 --> 20:39.613
Anyone makes a fuss,

20:39.696 --> 20:43.367
she has very heavy connections.

20:43.450 --> 20:45.160
- Connections to who?

20:45.243 --> 20:48.330
- That's way above
my paygrade, mate.

20:48.413 --> 20:49.498
I swear.

20:49.581 --> 20:52.417
I swear I would tell you
if I knew.

20:52.501 --> 20:54.419
♪ ♪

20:54.503 --> 20:55.379
- Hmm.

20:55.462 --> 21:01.843
♪ ♪

21:01.927 --> 21:03.679
[utensils clinking]

21:03.762 --> 21:07.891
- So, Thomas,
do you enjoy being a doctor?

21:09.184 --> 21:10.602
- I do.

21:10.686 --> 21:13.522
Uh, it feels good to know
that every day

21:13.605 --> 21:17.025
I'm helping someone
in a practical way.

21:17.109 --> 21:18.902
It's very fulfilling.

21:18.986 --> 21:20.696
- One of these days,
you're gonna have to stop

21:20.779 --> 21:23.991
being so damn saintly and come
work for your old man, huh?

21:24.074 --> 21:25.993
- Uh...

21:29.079 --> 21:31.540
- Martha, you work for
the government, as I recall.

21:31.623 --> 21:33.333
- Mm-hmm,
the Public Records Office.

21:33.417 --> 21:34.918
- Sounds fascinating.

21:35.002 --> 21:38.255
- Oh, a glorified librarian,
really, but I enjoy it.

21:38.338 --> 21:39.715
- You must have stamina.

21:39.798 --> 21:42.676
Most women find motherhood
taxing enough.

21:42.759 --> 21:45.554
- Yes, I have great stamina.

21:45.637 --> 21:47.514
And Thomas is
a wonderful father.

21:47.597 --> 21:49.808
- Mm, why, thank you.

21:49.891 --> 21:51.643
And you guys have met
Mrs. Pennyworth.

21:51.727 --> 21:53.520
I mean, we couldn't do it
without her.

21:53.603 --> 21:55.731
- Yes, she is a treasure.

21:55.814 --> 21:57.607
- What do you do, Virginia?

21:58.942 --> 22:02.612
- Keeping Patrick happy
is a full-time job.

22:02.696 --> 22:04.573
- I bet.

22:04.656 --> 22:06.742
And what brings
you two lovebirds

22:06.825 --> 22:09.995
to Jolly Old England?

22:10.078 --> 22:12.039
- Well, to be honest,
it's simple really.

22:12.122 --> 22:14.541
I missed my son.

22:14.624 --> 22:16.168
There's been a distance
between us,

22:16.251 --> 22:20.130
and, uh, I'd like to fix that
if I can.

22:21.590 --> 22:22.883
Blood is blood.

22:22.966 --> 22:24.176
Right, son?

22:24.259 --> 22:27.179
[dramatic music]

22:27.262 --> 22:28.263
♪ ♪

22:28.346 --> 22:29.556
- Right.

22:30.932 --> 22:33.143
It's damn strange
seeing him again.

22:33.226 --> 22:35.270
[water running]
- [spits]

22:35.353 --> 22:37.606
- All of a sudden,
I felt 12 years old.

22:37.689 --> 22:39.775
- They're kind of weird,
aren't they?

22:41.860 --> 22:43.820
Even for people like them.

22:43.904 --> 22:45.614
[water stops]

22:45.697 --> 22:48.575
- You mean
even for people like me?

22:48.658 --> 22:51.119
- [chuckles]

22:51.203 --> 22:53.371
Even for people like you.

22:53.455 --> 22:56.208
- Hmm.
[chuckles]

22:58.293 --> 23:00.378
[clears throat]

23:03.548 --> 23:06.927
It's been so long
since we last spoke properly.

23:07.010 --> 23:08.762
I...

23:08.845 --> 23:11.014
I don't know
who he is anymore.

23:12.808 --> 23:14.851
I'm not sure I want to know.

23:14.935 --> 23:16.478
- You barely said a word.

23:16.561 --> 23:18.396
- Well, I think you said enough
for the both of us.

23:18.480 --> 23:21.066
- Sorry.
I was kind of nervy.

23:21.149 --> 23:22.984
- No, don't be sorry.

23:23.068 --> 23:25.070
You stood up for yourself.

23:25.153 --> 23:27.155
I was proud of you.

23:27.239 --> 23:29.908
- You handled yourself
very well, too.

23:29.991 --> 23:31.535
- Mm.

23:31.618 --> 23:33.620
- It's funny that
he would just show up

23:33.703 --> 23:35.163
out of the blue like this.

23:35.247 --> 23:37.707
What do you think
he wants here?

23:37.791 --> 23:40.544
- What he said, I guess.
He--he wanted to meet Samantha.

23:40.627 --> 23:43.547
- You think?
- What else?

23:45.590 --> 23:48.343
- Does he have any
U.S. government connections?

23:48.426 --> 23:49.594
- Yeah, sure.
Of course.

23:49.678 --> 23:50.887
He runs a massive corporation.

23:50.971 --> 23:53.306
He is bound
to have government ties.

23:53.390 --> 23:55.225
What would that have to do
with anything?

23:55.308 --> 23:57.644
- Nothing.
I don't know.

24:00.063 --> 24:02.274
I was just wondering, but...

24:03.942 --> 24:06.111
He's here to see Samantha.

24:15.287 --> 24:17.664
- Martha.
- What?

24:17.747 --> 24:20.292
- What would his government
ties have to do with anything?

24:20.375 --> 24:22.627
- Nothing, Thomas.

24:22.711 --> 24:25.297
I was just thinking out loud.

24:30.135 --> 24:33.263
[TV static whirring]

24:53.575 --> 24:56.494
[baby babbles]

24:56.578 --> 25:00.874
- Oh, did I doze off?

25:00.957 --> 25:03.084
- Just for a second maybe.

25:05.337 --> 25:07.547
- [chuckles softly]
Babies, eh?

25:07.631 --> 25:09.507
They make you sleepy.

25:11.718 --> 25:13.595
[sighs]

25:16.389 --> 25:18.391
You two ready to talk?

25:18.475 --> 25:21.144
- I swear on the baby's life,
we don't know anything.

25:21.228 --> 25:23.146
- You shouldn't swear
on her life.

25:23.230 --> 25:24.940
Not on the baby.

25:25.023 --> 25:28.485
Don't worry, sweetheart.
She didn't mean it.

25:28.568 --> 25:30.779
She's just scared.

25:30.862 --> 25:34.032
[baby crying]
Oh. Oh, boy.

25:34.115 --> 25:36.785
There you go, darling.

25:36.868 --> 25:38.495
There you go.

25:38.578 --> 25:40.038
[baby whines]

25:40.121 --> 25:43.208
Sleep on, darling.
Sleep on.

25:50.131 --> 25:51.383
- Freeze.

25:56.221 --> 25:58.598
Say something now,
you crazy bitch.

25:58.682 --> 26:00.517
Say something now.

26:06.439 --> 26:09.276
- Sticks and stones, love.

26:09.359 --> 26:11.987
[kick thuds]
Sticks and stones.

26:12.070 --> 26:14.990
[ominous music]

26:15.073 --> 26:22.163
♪ ♪

26:36.594 --> 26:38.013
Bingo.

26:44.853 --> 26:48.857
- Martha's off to work early,
is she?

26:48.940 --> 26:50.650
- Uh-huh.

26:50.734 --> 26:52.277
And, uh, Virginia?

26:52.360 --> 26:54.779
- Shopping.

26:54.863 --> 26:57.365
I'm glad
it's just the two of us.

26:57.449 --> 27:00.118
- Oh, why's that?

27:00.201 --> 27:03.246
- I expect you're wondering
why I'm here.

27:04.456 --> 27:07.542
- Well, you told us.
You, uh...

27:07.625 --> 27:09.544
you missed me,

27:09.627 --> 27:12.547
and you wanted
to meet Martha and Samantha.

27:12.630 --> 27:14.049
- Well, of course.

27:14.132 --> 27:16.259
But I do have another reason.

27:18.386 --> 27:19.554
- What's that?

27:19.637 --> 27:21.389
- It's a Wayne Enterprises
issue.

27:21.473 --> 27:23.600
I think it's about time
you took some part

27:23.683 --> 27:25.560
in the family business,
don't you?

27:25.643 --> 27:28.396
- Well, I-I guess that depends.

27:28.480 --> 27:32.400
- What I'm about to tell you
is highly sensitive

27:32.484 --> 27:33.985
and confidential.

27:34.069 --> 27:36.196
I need your help, son.

27:36.279 --> 27:39.532
- [inhales deeply]

27:39.616 --> 27:40.909
Go on.

27:40.992 --> 27:43.119
- An employee
of Wayne Enterprises

27:43.203 --> 27:44.579
has gone missing

27:44.662 --> 27:46.748
with priceless
proprietary information.

27:46.831 --> 27:48.917
- What information?
- Complicated to explain.

27:49.000 --> 27:51.753
It's top-secret,
need-to-know sort of thing.

27:51.836 --> 27:55.298
We believe our employee,
Dr. Glubb, is in England.

27:55.382 --> 27:58.343
We believe he may try
to sell what he knows

27:58.426 --> 28:00.887
to the English government.

28:00.970 --> 28:03.056
- Well, that's too bad,

28:03.139 --> 28:06.267
but, um, what's it got
to do with me?

28:06.351 --> 28:08.686
- If we lose control
of this information,

28:08.770 --> 28:10.772
it could mean
the end of the company--

28:10.855 --> 28:13.566
total disaster for us all,

28:13.650 --> 28:16.528
for the Wayne family.

28:16.611 --> 28:18.613
- What can I do?

28:18.696 --> 28:20.532
- You could ask Martha
for help.

28:20.615 --> 28:22.909
- Martha?
Why Martha?

28:22.992 --> 28:25.328
- She'll know
if this man has tried

28:25.412 --> 28:27.288
to contact
the English government.

28:27.372 --> 28:31.209
Might even know where he is.
- Well, I very much doubt it.

28:31.292 --> 28:33.628
She works in admin
for the Public Records Office.

28:33.711 --> 28:36.005
- Come on,
I know that's just her cover.

28:36.089 --> 28:36.965
- Her cover?

28:37.048 --> 28:38.508
No, that's her job.

28:38.591 --> 28:40.427
- Thomas, I know
all about Martha.

28:40.510 --> 28:44.055
I know she's an active field
officer for MI5 science wing,

28:44.139 --> 28:45.682
troubleshooter
for the prime minister,

28:45.765 --> 28:47.142
licensed to kill, all that.

28:47.225 --> 28:50.061
This sort of case is
her responsibility.

28:50.145 --> 28:53.648
- Uh, well, uh,
you've been misinformed.

28:53.731 --> 28:55.650
She gave up that kind of work
same time I did,

28:55.733 --> 28:57.110
when Samantha was born.

28:59.821 --> 29:02.574
- I'm sorry.
I-I thought you knew.

29:02.657 --> 29:04.492
I didn't mean
to cause trouble.

29:04.576 --> 29:06.661
- Who told you this?

29:06.744 --> 29:09.456
- We're in a tough situation
here, son, very tough,

29:09.539 --> 29:10.540
or I wouldn't ask
for your help.

29:10.623 --> 29:12.000
- Who told you?

29:12.083 --> 29:14.043
- I have contacts at the
Pentagon, reliable contacts.

29:14.127 --> 29:15.587
- Well, they're not as reliable
as you think.

29:15.670 --> 29:17.338
- Maybe, but the fact remains,
Thomas--

29:17.422 --> 29:19.591
- Let's get one thing straight.

29:19.674 --> 29:22.051
Martha and I made
a very conscious decision

29:22.135 --> 29:25.054
to quit that world
and lead normal,

29:25.138 --> 29:27.682
clean, useful lives.

29:27.765 --> 29:31.186
No lies, no violence,

29:31.269 --> 29:33.354
no power games.

29:33.438 --> 29:36.691
Martha doesn't work
for the MI5 or the PM's office.

29:36.774 --> 29:38.276
And even if she did,
which she doesn't,

29:38.359 --> 29:40.904
there's no way I'd ask her
to break the trust of...

29:40.987 --> 29:43.698
whoever the hell
she works for, okay?

29:43.781 --> 29:46.743
[dramatic music]

29:46.826 --> 29:49.204
♪ ♪

29:49.287 --> 29:52.123
Now I've got to get going.

29:52.207 --> 29:59.297
♪ ♪

30:03.718 --> 30:05.929
- I can go over that wall
and get to the roof

30:06.012 --> 30:07.388
by way of that drainpipe there

30:07.472 --> 30:09.641
and then in
through the skylight.

30:11.476 --> 30:14.437
- Or we could just knock
on the door.

30:14.521 --> 30:16.314
- But where's the fun in that?

30:16.397 --> 30:19.317
[ominous music]

30:19.400 --> 30:26.491
♪ ♪

30:34.332 --> 30:37.669
- It's a job, Daveboy.
Jobs aren't meant to be fun.

30:37.752 --> 30:40.505
♪ ♪

30:40.588 --> 30:43.424
We'd like to speak
to Sister Susie, please.

30:43.508 --> 30:47.470
- Sister sees unclean souls
with an appointment.

30:48.763 --> 30:50.265
Hey.
- Who are you calling unclean?

30:50.348 --> 30:51.599
- Hey! Whoa!

30:51.683 --> 30:54.644
[distant chanting]

30:54.727 --> 31:00.817
♪ ♪

31:08.032 --> 31:09.242
[door opens]

31:11.369 --> 31:18.459
♪ ♪

31:22.297 --> 31:24.799
[door closes]
- For fuck sakes, Robert.

31:24.882 --> 31:28.303
- They just barged in.
I couldn't stop 'em.

31:31.723 --> 31:34.601
- Welcome.
How can we help you?

31:34.684 --> 31:37.645
- We're looking
for a Jessica Thistle.

31:37.729 --> 31:40.523
- Aw.
No, man, you're not.

31:40.607 --> 31:41.983
- No?
- No.

31:42.066 --> 31:44.235
You're looking
for something else entirely.

31:44.319 --> 31:47.488
You're looking
for a purpose in life.

31:47.572 --> 31:48.656
But there are none.

31:48.740 --> 31:51.159
We are the dust
of ancient stars.

31:51.242 --> 31:53.036
Everything else in imaginary--

31:53.119 --> 31:55.330
just stories we tell ourselves.

31:55.413 --> 31:57.332
- She's not wrong.

31:58.958 --> 32:01.461
- Well, let's just say that the
imaginary police turned up here

32:01.544 --> 32:04.255
and told themselves they were
taking your dust to the nick.

32:04.339 --> 32:07.133
- Ooh, what would
the charge be?

32:07.216 --> 32:09.636
- Well, from what I hear,
kidnapping,

32:09.719 --> 32:12.013
false imprisonment,
and sex trafficking,

32:12.096 --> 32:14.015
just for a start.

32:14.098 --> 32:15.933
- Oh, do fuck off.

32:16.017 --> 32:18.561
This is a registered charity.

32:18.645 --> 32:21.147
And I'm extremely
well protected.

32:21.230 --> 32:23.775
- That's just a story
you tell yourself.

32:25.151 --> 32:28.363
Now give us Jessica Thistle,
and we'll be on our way.

32:30.698 --> 32:33.993
- Mm, if she wants
to go with you, she can.

32:34.077 --> 32:37.789
If she doesn't,
you can fuck off, okay?

32:37.872 --> 32:38.956
- Fair enough.

32:39.040 --> 32:44.212
♪ ♪

32:44.295 --> 32:47.215
[keys jingling]

32:47.298 --> 32:49.425
[lock clicking]

32:49.509 --> 32:56.599
♪ ♪

33:01.562 --> 33:03.731
Hello, Jessica.

33:03.815 --> 33:04.899
- Hi.

33:04.982 --> 33:06.567
- Jessica, my name's Alfie.

33:06.651 --> 33:09.404
I'm here to take you home.

33:09.487 --> 33:11.030
- I don't want to go home.

33:11.114 --> 33:13.032
- There's your answer.
Fuck off.

33:13.116 --> 33:14.909
- I lied.
We're taking her anyway.

33:14.992 --> 33:16.285
- Oh, for fuck's sake.

33:16.369 --> 33:19.038
What a vulgar, boring
little thug you are.

33:19.122 --> 33:20.373
Robert!

33:20.456 --> 33:21.874
- Now, there's no need
for trouble, love.

33:21.958 --> 33:23.584
- Oh, no trouble.
[door closes]

33:23.668 --> 33:24.794
Karma.

33:27.004 --> 33:28.339
- Daveboy, you deal with him.

33:28.423 --> 33:30.883
I'll take the girl.
- [chuckles] No.

33:30.967 --> 33:32.969
No, this is a new jacket.

33:33.052 --> 33:35.138
- Well, you've already
got it dirty.

33:36.514 --> 33:37.807
- Where?

33:37.890 --> 33:40.143
- There.

33:40.226 --> 33:42.103
- Shit.

33:42.186 --> 33:44.772
Fine, but next time, you're
doing the rough stuff, okay?

33:44.856 --> 33:47.066
- Mm-hmm.
Come here.

33:47.150 --> 33:48.443
- Out of my way.

33:50.403 --> 33:53.114
I said, "Out of my way."

33:55.575 --> 33:57.326
[scoffs]

33:58.578 --> 34:00.163
[all scream]

34:00.246 --> 34:04.125
- Come on.
[person whimpering]

34:04.208 --> 34:07.128
[tense music]

34:07.211 --> 34:14.302
♪ ♪

34:20.850 --> 34:22.477
Hey, you're all right, love.

34:22.560 --> 34:24.061
You're safe.

34:25.688 --> 34:28.483
I thought we'd let you sleep
a while before I take you home.

34:28.566 --> 34:30.568
- Home? No.

34:30.651 --> 34:32.528
Take me back to Sister Susie!

34:32.612 --> 34:35.114
- Hey, hey, hey.

34:35.198 --> 34:36.491
Come on.

34:39.076 --> 34:41.496
- [crying]
I don't want to go home.

34:41.579 --> 34:43.164
- Give over.

34:43.247 --> 34:45.291
- Why not?

34:45.374 --> 34:48.044
- They don't like me,
and I don't like them.

34:48.127 --> 34:49.504
- Your mum and dad?

34:49.587 --> 34:51.756
Of course you do.
Of course they do.

34:52.715 --> 34:54.258
- You don't know them.

34:56.928 --> 34:59.847
- Look...

34:59.931 --> 35:03.684
I used to think
I hated my dad...

35:03.768 --> 35:05.686
but I didn't really.

35:05.770 --> 35:08.272
I didn't understand him.

35:08.356 --> 35:10.274
Different.

35:10.358 --> 35:11.651
- You wait and see.

35:11.734 --> 35:13.986
They'll be happy
to have you back.

35:14.070 --> 35:17.990
- I don't want to go there.
Please don't make me.

35:18.074 --> 35:20.326
[crying]

35:20.409 --> 35:23.955
- Listen, we've been paid
to get you home, that's all.

35:24.038 --> 35:26.833
- So never mind me
as long as you get your money?

35:26.916 --> 35:28.709
- No.

35:28.793 --> 35:31.754
We just have to get you home.

35:31.838 --> 35:34.632
If you don't want to stay,
you don't have to stay.

35:34.715 --> 35:36.843
- [crying]

35:36.926 --> 35:39.345
- [sighs]
Look...

35:41.722 --> 35:45.434
Here's my, um, office number
and home address.

35:49.522 --> 35:53.067
If you do go off again,
don't go back to Sister Susie.

35:53.150 --> 35:56.279
She's not kosher,
that one.

35:56.362 --> 35:57.822
Call us or come around,

35:57.905 --> 36:00.408
and we'll find you
somewhere safe to lay low.

36:00.491 --> 36:01.409
All right?

36:01.492 --> 36:04.412
[dramatic music]

36:04.495 --> 36:11.586
♪ ♪

36:32.148 --> 36:34.442
- Job done?

36:34.525 --> 36:37.278
- Job done.

36:37.361 --> 36:39.614
[sighs]

36:39.697 --> 36:41.782
- So what's wrong?

36:41.866 --> 36:43.784
Money for jam.

36:43.868 --> 36:46.579
- No, I'm not complaining.

36:46.662 --> 36:49.916
It is sad, though, innit?

36:49.999 --> 36:53.461
When you look at all
the freedom, prosperity,

36:53.544 --> 36:56.213
and opportunity that we have

36:56.297 --> 36:59.175
and all these lost souls
in the world

36:59.258 --> 37:02.261
looking for answers,
looking for a home.

37:02.345 --> 37:03.763
Then there's me,

37:03.846 --> 37:05.890
on top of the world,
happy as a lark,

37:05.973 --> 37:08.976
rolling in bunce,
and for what?

37:09.060 --> 37:11.520
Kicking squaddies
in the bollocks?

37:11.604 --> 37:13.022
What's wrong with the world,
Daveboy?

37:13.105 --> 37:15.399
Where are the moral values?
Thanks.

37:15.483 --> 37:17.985
- Soft git.
- I'm not.

37:18.069 --> 37:19.362
- You're taking soft git

37:19.445 --> 37:21.155
to a whole new fucking level,
my friend.

37:21.239 --> 37:23.658
- But am I wrong?
- Of course not.

37:23.741 --> 37:27.328
But we're all just dust,
like the hippy lady said.

37:27.411 --> 37:30.873
No point in greeting about it
like a big fucking baby.

37:30.957 --> 37:32.667
- Forget I spoke.
[door opens]

37:32.750 --> 37:34.627
- Already did.

37:34.710 --> 37:36.379
[door closes]

37:36.462 --> 37:38.005
[footsteps approaching]

37:42.259 --> 37:44.428
- Afternoon.

37:44.512 --> 37:45.680
- Hey.

37:47.098 --> 37:49.100
- Hard day?

37:49.183 --> 37:50.476
- Up and down.

37:50.559 --> 37:52.895
- What's the pram for?

37:52.979 --> 37:54.563
- Fuck do you think it's for?

37:54.647 --> 37:57.316
- Babies, usually.
- Well, then.

37:57.400 --> 37:59.068
- You ain't got a baby
in there.

37:59.151 --> 38:01.696
- Have I not?
There's a relief.

38:01.779 --> 38:03.990
- Look, you're supposed to be
working for me, you know?

38:04.073 --> 38:07.535
I pay your wages.
- Stuff your wages.

38:07.618 --> 38:09.870
- Nice. Cheers.

38:10.955 --> 38:13.499
- Actually, no.

38:13.582 --> 38:15.084
Sorry, Alfie.

38:15.167 --> 38:18.004
I'm in a right mood,
and I were lashing out.

38:18.087 --> 38:19.755
I retract that comment.

38:19.839 --> 38:21.173
- Retraction accepted.

38:21.257 --> 38:22.883
- There's a baby in there.

38:22.967 --> 38:26.053
[baby babbling]

38:28.222 --> 38:30.725
- Fuck me, there is.

38:30.808 --> 38:32.268
What have you done now, Bet?

38:32.351 --> 38:35.980
- Nice little thing.
Doesn't fuss.

38:36.063 --> 38:38.607
[chuckles softly]

38:38.691 --> 38:40.109
Name's Julie.

38:40.192 --> 38:44.113
- A baby with blood on her.
You're potty, you are.

38:44.196 --> 38:48.034
- I found a Raven ledger
with codenames and addresses,

38:48.117 --> 38:50.953
a whole network
of the bastards.

38:51.037 --> 38:52.413
I'll find John Salt,

38:52.496 --> 38:56.292
and I'll scrag him this time
good and proper.

38:56.375 --> 38:58.377
I just need you to babysit.

38:58.461 --> 38:59.754
[baby babbles]

38:59.837 --> 39:02.465
- Bet, I don't know nothing
about babies.

39:02.548 --> 39:04.008
I don't like babies.

39:04.091 --> 39:05.718
- No, no.
Me neither.

39:05.801 --> 39:08.846
Can you not ask Peggy, eh?

39:08.929 --> 39:12.683
- Peggy's 100 miles away,
and she'd say no any road.

39:15.186 --> 39:17.146
What about your mum?
She around?

39:17.229 --> 39:19.482
- My mom's already got a job.

39:19.565 --> 39:22.943
Bet, forget about John Salt.
Get on with your life.

39:23.027 --> 39:26.614
- Okay, on me own then,
as usual.

39:26.697 --> 39:28.491
- Bet, don't be like that.
Look, wait.

39:28.574 --> 39:31.035
- No, no,
I know who me friends are.

39:31.118 --> 39:33.120
Come on, Julie.
We'll go elsewhere.

39:33.204 --> 39:36.248
We know where we're not wanted.
[door opens]

39:36.332 --> 39:39.210
- See what I mean?
Where are the moral values?

39:39.293 --> 39:41.003
- [chuckles]
[door closes]

39:41.087 --> 39:42.630
- Hey.
- [gasps]

39:42.713 --> 39:44.673
Hey.
- Daddy!

39:44.757 --> 39:46.133
- There she is.
- Yay!

39:46.217 --> 39:49.220
- Oh, come here.
Oh, glad to see you, sweetie.

39:49.303 --> 39:50.888
Mm.

39:50.971 --> 39:52.973
Hey.
How was your day?

39:53.057 --> 39:54.892
- It was boring, as usual.

39:54.975 --> 39:56.310
Yours?

39:56.393 --> 39:59.396
- Uh, same.
- Mm.

40:02.066 --> 40:03.442
- Uh, you're back early.

40:03.526 --> 40:05.319
- I felt like
I wanted to be home with Sam,

40:05.402 --> 40:06.862
so I took the afternoon off.

40:06.946 --> 40:09.156
- [gasps]
Well, me too.

40:09.240 --> 40:12.368
- Mm, great minds, huh?
- Mm.

40:12.451 --> 40:15.538
Is my--is my dad home?
- Mm-hmm, in their room.

40:15.621 --> 40:20.126
Virginia just got back
from sightseeing and shopping.

40:20.209 --> 40:24.171
My God, she knows how to shop.
- Mm.

40:24.255 --> 40:25.631
Did, um--

40:25.714 --> 40:27.883
did he speak to you at all?
- No.

40:27.967 --> 40:31.637
I mean, we spoke, but not about
anything in particular, really.

40:31.720 --> 40:34.181
Why?
Did you speak with him?

40:34.265 --> 40:36.725
- I did.
- And?

40:36.809 --> 40:40.020
- Why?
- "Why"?

40:40.104 --> 40:42.314
- Well, uh, why did you ask?

40:42.398 --> 40:44.692
- No reason.

40:44.775 --> 40:46.360
Just making conversation.

40:46.443 --> 40:47.945
He might have said
why he's here.

40:48.028 --> 40:51.031
- He didn't.
He said, uh...

40:51.115 --> 40:53.075
Well, he said a lot of things.

40:53.159 --> 40:55.035
Nothing important.

40:55.119 --> 40:57.204
Whoa, Sam, that is--
- Oh!

40:57.288 --> 40:58.956
- That is so great.
- [laughs]

40:59.039 --> 41:02.293
- Oh! Well, now we got
to build another one.

41:02.376 --> 41:04.044
[chuckles]

41:04.128 --> 41:06.505
- Well, um, that's great.

41:06.589 --> 41:08.257
I guess he's actually here
to see Sam.

41:08.340 --> 41:09.383
- Mm.
- Me!

41:09.466 --> 41:10.759
Here to see me!
- Yes.

41:10.843 --> 41:12.052
That's right, honey.

41:12.136 --> 41:13.679
He's here to see you.

41:21.854 --> 41:22.938
- Well?

41:23.022 --> 41:25.357
- I'm working on it.

41:25.441 --> 41:28.485
- Did you talk to him?
- I did.

41:29.820 --> 41:31.280
- And?

41:31.363 --> 41:34.658
- I said
I'm working on it.

41:34.742 --> 41:37.244
- What does that mean?
- [sighs]

41:37.328 --> 41:40.039
He didn't even know
she was active MI5, okay?

41:40.122 --> 41:42.166
That's--that's
what I'm working with.

41:42.249 --> 41:44.752
- He said that?
- Yeah, okay?

41:44.835 --> 41:46.795
So give me some time.

41:48.380 --> 41:50.090
- And you believed him?

41:50.174 --> 41:52.009
- Yeah, I did.
He's my son.

41:52.092 --> 41:54.261
I know him.
- [chuckles]

41:54.345 --> 41:57.389
You're telling me you're
a good judge of character?

41:57.473 --> 41:59.600
Me, of all people?
- Fuck you.

41:59.683 --> 42:01.393
- Excuse me?

42:04.021 --> 42:06.941
- I know my own son.
He doesn't know anything.

42:07.024 --> 42:09.026
It's gonna take some time
to make this work.

42:09.109 --> 42:10.444
That's all I'm saying.
- No.

42:10.527 --> 42:12.279
What you said was eff you.

42:12.363 --> 42:15.366
That's what you said to me.
- For which, I apologize.

42:15.449 --> 42:17.618
This is a tense situation.
I'm tense.

42:17.701 --> 42:18.953
- I understand you're tense,

42:19.036 --> 42:21.455
but you don't speak to me
like that.

42:21.538 --> 42:25.125
You know I can't tolerate
bad language.

42:25.209 --> 42:27.962
I shared that with you.
- Ginny, I understand--

42:28.045 --> 42:30.214
- You don't understand
anything.

42:30.297 --> 42:32.258
Not even your own son.

42:32.341 --> 42:34.301
He knows what she does.

42:34.385 --> 42:35.719
He was playing you.

42:35.803 --> 42:37.179
Look at me!

42:38.681 --> 42:40.182
Say it.

42:41.850 --> 42:44.186
- He was playing me.

42:44.270 --> 42:47.273
I'll talk to him again.
- Don't take no for an answer.

42:47.356 --> 42:48.732
You're his father.

42:50.943 --> 42:55.864
I am mandated to do whatever
I need to do to get a win here.

42:55.948 --> 42:58.409
Not just allowed...

42:58.492 --> 43:00.619
mandated...

43:00.703 --> 43:05.040
whatever I need to do.

43:05.124 --> 43:08.002
Understand?

43:08.085 --> 43:11.213
[cell phone ringing]

43:13.507 --> 43:15.092
[cell phone beeps]

43:15.175 --> 43:17.094
Tell me something good.

43:17.177 --> 43:20.931
- The girl is in place.
Shall we proceed?

43:21.015 --> 43:22.516
- Yes, go ahead.

43:22.599 --> 43:25.352
You have the green light
for tomorrow morning.

43:25.436 --> 43:28.355
[haunting music]

43:28.439 --> 43:30.691
♪ ♪

43:30.774 --> 43:36.655
- ♪ I can't just forget ♪

43:36.739 --> 43:42.953
♪ My darling,
I'll never know why ♪

43:43.037 --> 43:46.415
♪ You left
without saying

43:46.498 --> 43:50.085
♪ Bye-bye ♪

43:50.169 --> 43:57.259
♪ ♪

44:13.984 --> 44:16.070
- [inhales sharply]

44:20.783 --> 44:22.659
[sighs]

44:29.750 --> 44:34.171
- [inhales deeply,
exhales slowly]

44:34.254 --> 44:35.672
Right.

44:39.134 --> 44:42.054
[sighs]
[line trilling]

44:42.137 --> 44:43.263
Oh, yes.

44:43.347 --> 44:45.099
Hello.
Good morning.

44:45.182 --> 44:47.017
Um, I'm calling in response

44:47.101 --> 44:50.270
to your advertisement
in the newspaper.

44:50.354 --> 44:52.398
Yeah.
Yeah, that's right.

44:52.481 --> 44:54.024
[chuckles] My name is--
[door closes]

44:54.108 --> 44:56.985
Oh, no, we don't want any.
Thank you very much.

44:57.069 --> 44:59.822
Uh, but nice of you to call.

44:59.905 --> 45:02.366
Blimey, salesman.

45:04.159 --> 45:05.828
They don't stop, do they?

45:05.911 --> 45:07.371
- You phoned them, didn't you?

45:07.454 --> 45:09.623
- Me? No.

45:09.706 --> 45:11.291
- Well, I didn't hear
the phone ring.

45:11.375 --> 45:14.378
- Well, it did. Otherwise,
why would I answer it?

45:16.463 --> 45:18.132
You all right?

45:18.215 --> 45:20.426
Wrong side of the bed?
- Yeah.

45:20.509 --> 45:22.761
No, bad dream.

45:22.845 --> 45:24.638
- Was your father in it?
- No.

45:24.721 --> 45:26.807
- Ooh, he's been bothering me
in my dreams,

45:26.890 --> 45:28.308
something chronic--

45:28.392 --> 45:31.061
leaping out from dark corners
like an hobgoblin.

45:31.145 --> 45:32.271
Does he do that with you?

45:32.354 --> 45:34.481
- No.
It's a girl I know.

45:34.565 --> 45:38.277
- Oh, well, that sort of dream.

45:38.360 --> 45:40.821
[sighs]

45:40.904 --> 45:43.782
When are you gonna
settle down, Alfie?

45:43.866 --> 45:45.409
You need children.
[doorbell rings]

45:45.492 --> 45:48.120
- You keep telling me that,
but you never say why.

45:48.203 --> 45:49.496
I mean, what are they for?

45:49.580 --> 45:51.832
My life's pukka as it is.

45:55.919 --> 45:57.171
- Help me.

45:57.254 --> 46:00.174
[ominous music]

46:00.257 --> 46:02.509
♪ ♪

46:02.593 --> 46:03.927
- Oh!

46:04.011 --> 46:09.600
♪ ♪
